<br>
2) It'd just be used to bypass a lot of content that people would fight through normally, just because an invis would be guaranteed to wear off.  The only solution to this would be to make <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>everywhere</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> you wanted people to fight through contain see-invis mobs, which I don't view as a good thing.  (Something EQ devs would have been wise to learn a long time ago- avoid making decisions which restrict your options in the future).<br>
<br>
3) Kind of tying in with #2- what you're essentially doing is giving every class improved invisibility.  One of the things that makes the spell so dandy is that it's self-only; go from playing a wizard to a class w/o improved invis (bards notwithstanding) and you'll gain a whole new appreciation for it.  It would take variance out of the game, and classes are already overlapping each other too much.<br>
<br>
Nice idea, but I think that the disadvantages of having the spell in game outweigh any advantage that would come by putting it in. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=danenel>Danenel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Member of Team Xuzl</span><br>  Posts: 2302<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/26/03 6:36 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Targetable Imp Invis...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>2) It'd just be used to bypass a lot of content that people would fight through normally, just because an invis would be guaranteed to wear off.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
